\par }{\b\f15 (2)\tab Q. How can I make the game run faster?
\par }{\f15 
\par }{\b\f15 A.}{\f15 \tab 
If you have a computer whose configuration is close to the minimum system requirements for running Midtown Madness, switching to a lower resolution setting may make the game run faster (the safest resolution settings are 320x200, 320x240, and 640x480).
\line \line To switch to a lower resolution, click Options (in the upper right corner of any game screen), and then click Graphics Options. In the Resolution list, pick a lower resolution setting, and then click Done.
\par \line If you have an older video card, setting your Renderer setting to Software Renderer and turning on the Interlaced Rendering option (only available when Software Renderer is selected in the Renderer list) may also make the game run faster.
\par \line }{\b\f15 Other suggestions for making the game run faster:\line }{\f15 Turning on the Sp
eed Loading option in Graphics Options (Options menu) may make the game run faster on your computer. With Speed Loading turned on, the game will wait to load new textures and geometry until you actually encounter them. The downside to turning on Speed Loa
ding is that Midtown Madness may pause occasionally during gameplay. If that is the case, turn off Speed Loading.\line \line You can also try other methods to reduce the pausing effect:\line --Reduce your Texture Resolution setting in Graphics Options.
\line --Reduce your Far Clip Pane setting in Graphics Options.\line --Reduce your Audio Quality setting in Audio Options.\line --Close all open applications before starting Midtown Madness. \line --Install more RAM on your computer.\line \line 
Although the advanced physics model featured in Midtown Madnes
s is designed to maintain an accurate simulation experience even at relatively slow frame rates, you can also try the following to make the game run even faster (listed in approximate order of effectiveness):\line 
--Reduce your Resolution setting in Graphic Options.\line --If your Renderer setting is set to Software Renderer, turn off Textured Sky or turn on the Interlaced Rendering option in Graphics Options.\line 
--If you have an older 3D hardware accelerator card, or if your Renderer setting is set to Software Renderer, turn off the Textured Sky option in Graphics Options (if Interlaced Rendering is also turned on, turning off Textured Sky will have no effect).
\line --If you have an older 3D hardware accelerator card, setting your Renderer setting to Software Renderer may improve performance.\line --Reduce your Object Detail setting in Graphics Options.\line 
--Turn on the Hide Pedestrians option in Graphics Options.\line --Turn off the Cloud Shadows and Vehicle Reflections options in Graphic Options.\line --While you are racing or cruising, turn off the rearview mirror by pressing BACKSPACE.\line 
--Race (or cruise) in cockpit view with the dashboard turned off (press D to toggle the dashboard on and off).\line --Reduce your Texture Resolution setting in Graphics Options.\line \line The "Video Card Notes and Troubles
hooting" section of README.RTF (located in the folder where you installed Midtown Madness or on the Midtown Madness disc) also includes valuable information about optimizing your Graphics settings.
